---
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";
import { CONFIG } from "../lib/config";
---

<Layout title="Guide - SF API Version Updater">
  <div class="guide-wrap">
    <h1 class="guide-heading">User Guide</h1>

    <div class="guide-sections">
      <!-- What it does -->
      <section class="card guide-section">
        <h2 class="guide-section-title">What this tool does</h2>
        <p class="guide-p">
          Updates the <code class="inline-code">apiVersion</code> field in your Salesforce
          metadata. It does <strong>not</strong> modify any code, logic, or configuration,
          only the API version number.
        </p>
        <p class="guide-p">
          Keeping metadata on a current API version ensures access to the latest
          platform features and avoids deprecated API behavior.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Supported types -->
      <section class="card guide-section">
        <h2 class="guide-section-title">Supported metadata types</h2>
        <ul class="guide-list">
          <li><strong>Apex Classes</strong> (.cls)</li>
          <li><strong>Apex Triggers</strong> (.trigger)</li>
          <li><strong>Visualforce Pages</strong> (.page)</li>
          <li><strong>Visualforce Components</strong> (.component)</li>
          <li><strong>Aura Components</strong> (Aura bundles)</li>
          <li><strong>Lightning Web Components</strong> (LWC bundles)</li>
          <li>
            <strong>Flows</strong> (deploying creates a new version, the tool optionally
            cleans up obsolete versions)
          </li>
        </ul>
        <p class="guide-note">
          Only unmanaged components are shown. Managed package components are
          excluded.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Package Installation -->
      <section id="why-install" class="card guide-section guide-section-accent">
        <h2 class="guide-section-title guide-section-title-sm">
          Step 0: Install the package
          <span class="guide-section-subtitle">(once per org)</span>
        </h2>
        <p class="guide-p guide-p-sm">
          SF API Version Updater uses a free managed package to register the
          OAuth connection. Salesforce is retiring legacy Connected Apps in
          favor of External Client Apps, which must be installed in each org
          before they can authorize users.
          <strong>Only needs to be done once per org.</strong>
        </p>

        <ol class="guide-list guide-list-spaced">
          <li>Click the install button for your org type below.</li>
          <li>
            You'll land on Salesforce's package install screen. Log in if
            prompted.
          </li>
          <li>
            Choose <strong>"Install for All Users"</strong> (or admins only).
          </li>
          <li>Click <strong>Install</strong>. May take a minute or two.</li>
          <li>Once done, come back and log in.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="guide-install-btns" id="guide-install-btns">
          <a
            href={CONFIG.PACKAGE_INSTALL_URL_PROD}
            target="_blank"
            rel="noopener"
            class="btn btn-primary btn-sm"
            >Install in Production / Developer Org</a
          >
          <a
            href={CONFIG.PACKAGE_INSTALL_URL_SANDBOX}
            target="_blank"
            rel="noopener"
            class="btn btn-secondary btn-sm">Install in Sandbox</a
          >
        </div>

        <p class="guide-note guide-note-sm">
          If you see an "app not installed" error when logging in, the tool will
          automatically redirect you here.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- How to use -->
      <section class="card guide-section">
        <h2 class="guide-section-title">How to use</h2>
        <ol class="guide-list">
          <li>
            <strong>Install the package</strong>: see Step 0 above. One-time per
            org.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Log in</strong>: click Login (Production) or Login (Sandbox)
            to authorize via OAuth.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Select metadata types</strong>: choose which types to review
            and click "Load Components."
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Review components</strong>: each row shows the current API
            version and a status:
            <span class="guide-pill-row">
              <span class="pill pill-current">Current</span>
              <span class="pill pill-outdated">Outdated</span>
              <span class="pill pill-deprecated">Deprecated</span>
            </span>
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Select components</strong>: use checkboxes, "Select all," or
            the search and filter controls.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Choose target version</strong>: defaults to the latest
            available API version.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Set test level</strong>: optionally run Apex tests during
            deployment. Failed tests trigger auto-rollback.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Backup</strong>: "Download backup first" is checked by
            default. Saves a ZIP of original metadata.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Update</strong>: click "Update Selected Components" and
            watch progress in the log panel.
          </li>
        </ol>
      </section>

      <!-- Flow versioning -->
      <section class="card guide-section">
        <h2 class="guide-section-title">Flow version management</h2>
        <p class="guide-p">
          Deploying an updated Flow creates a <strong>new version</strong>. The
          old version becomes inactive.
        </p>
        <p class="guide-p">
          Enable "Delete previous (inactive) Flow version after successful
          update" to clean up automatically. Leave it off if you want to keep
          the old version as a rollback point.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Security -->
      <section class="card guide-section">
        <h2 class="guide-section-title">Security &amp; privacy</h2>
        <ul class="guide-list">
          <li>Credentials are <strong>never stored</strong> on any server.</li>
          <li>
            Tokens live in browser session storage only (cleared when the tab
            closes).
          </li>
          <li>
            The Cloudflare Worker proxy is <strong>stateless</strong>: it
            forwards requests without storing data.
          </li>
          <li>Metadata is processed entirely in your browser memory.</li>
          <li>All traffic uses HTTPS.</li>
          <li>The source code is fully open source.</li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <!-- Prerequisites -->
      <section class="card guide-section">
        <h2 class="guide-section-title">Prerequisites</h2>
        <ul class="guide-list">
          <li>A Salesforce org (Production, Developer, or Sandbox)</li>
          <li>
            A user with <strong>API Access</strong> and <strong
              >Modify All Data</strong
            > or <strong>Author Apex</strong>
          </li>
          <li>For Flows: <strong>Manage Flows</strong> permission</li>
          <li>A modern browser (Chrome, Firefox, Edge, Safari)</li>
        </ul>
      </section>
    </div>
  </div>
</Layout>

<style>
  @keyframes highlight-pulse {
    0% {
      box-shadow: 0 0 0 0 rgba(37, 99, 235, 0.4);
    }
    50% {
      box-shadow: 0 0 0 8px rgba(37, 99, 235, 0.1);
    }
    100% {
      box-shadow: 0 0 0 0 rgba(37, 99, 235, 0);
    }
  }
  .highlight-anchor {
    animation: highlight-pulse 1.2s ease-out 0.2s 2;
  }
</style>

<script>
  if (window.location.hash === "#why-install") {
    const el = document.getElementById("why-install");
    if (el) {
      const headerHeight = 52 + 16; // sticky header + a little breathing room
      const top =
        el.getBoundingClientRect().top + window.scrollY - headerHeight;
      window.scrollTo({ top, behavior: "smooth" });
      el.classList.add("highlight-anchor");
    }
  }
</script>
